Anita Diamant 's superb book takes the well known story of Jacob and his 12 sons and gives voice to the women long silent . ||| 1
This work of historical fiction explores the experiences of the women in relation to their men as well as the relationships between the women . ||| 1
The first half of the book is the story of Jacob 's four wives : their love for the same man , their conflicts , and the bond between sisters and women . ||| 1
Each month the women join together in the red tent for several days . ||| 1
Rather than a source of disgrace , the book gives a reaffirming message of what it means to be a women and worships the ability to give life , which the mothers pass on to their daughter Dinah . ||| 1
As interesting as the relationships between the characters , the book presents a myriad of the religious practices of the time . ||| 1
Througout the book we see that the women continue to practice their own religious beliefs , until a dramatic conflict with Jacob . ||| 1
In the second half of the book , the reader is able to catch a glimpse of Egyptian gods and godesses . ||| 1
However , these mentions are often brief and may leave one wanting to hear more and explore the level of monotheism that was really practiced . ||| 1
The second half of the book follows Dinah into Egypt after she flees tragedy in Canaan . ||| 1
The second half is less interesting than the first , but the reading is fast and moves quickly . ||| 1
The portrayal of Joseph is a far cry from his broadway persona and there is little in the way of explanation for why he has become the greedy selfish man that he is . ||| 1
Dinah 's sotry ends with a bitterswee tone . ||| 1
After seeing her family from afar at her father 's death , she receives some sense of reconciliation from the family that remains . ||| 1
After returning to Egypt , Dinah dies surrounded by loved ones and returns to her waiting mothers . ||| 1
The ending offers some conclusion to the divides within her family and we see that life continues on . ||| 1
